          "title": "The covenant marriage — gift upon gift (16:8-14)",
          "body": "The allegory's second movement is the covenant-making itself. The same God who passed by when the infant was dying passes by again when she has 'reached the age for love' (16:8). The gesture is specific: 'I spread My skirt over you and covered your nakedness' — the identical idiom Boaz uses with Ruth (Ruth 3:9), the kinsman-redeemer gesture of claiming and protecting. God swears an oath, enters covenant, and Jerusalem becomes His (16:8). What follows is a cascade of gifts: washing, anointing with oil, embroidered cloth, fine leather sandals, fine linen, silk (16:9-10); jewelry — bracelets, necklace, ring, earrings, crown (16:11-12); food — fine flour, honey, oil (16:13). The inventory is not decorative; it maps onto the actual prosperity of Jerusalem under Solomon, when the city's fame 'went forth among the nations' (16:14) — just as 1 Kings 10:1-9 records the Queen of Sheba marveling at Solomon's wealth and wisdom. The chapter's 14th verse is the pivot and the pinnacle: 'your fame went forth among the nations on account of your beauty, for it was perfect because of My splendor which I bestowed on you.' Every gift was derivative, bestowed, not earned. The only beautiful thing about Jerusalem was God's own beauty reflected in her. This is the theological principle that makes the following apostasy so catastrophic: what was given was redirected, and what was reflected was claimed as self-originating."
