          "title": "The judgment — lovers become executioners (16:35-58)",
          "body": "The formal judgment oracle opens with the covenant-lawsuit formula: 'Therefore, O harlot, hear the word of the LORD' (16:35). The announced punishment is precisely symmetrical with the sin. The lovers she pursued will be gathered against her (16:37) — God turns her political alliances into instruments of punishment. They will tear down her shrines, demolish her high places, strip her clothing, take her jewels, and leave her 'naked and bare' (16:39) — the exact condition in which God had found her in the field (16:7). The mirroring is judicial: you used My gifts to betray Me; the nations I will gather will take those gifts back. The punishment is not disproportionate revenge; it is covenant-justice structured by the lex talionis. The comparative section (16:44-58) then introduces the sisters: Samaria and Sodom. This is the chapter's most rhetorically shocking passage. Sodom's guilt is named carefully — not primarily the sexual sin of Genesis 19, but 'arrogance, abundant food and careless ease, but she did not help the poor and needy' (16:49). Ezekiel's Sodom is characterized by self-satisfied prosperity that produces social injustice. Jerusalem had all of Sodom's wealth and spiritual privilege besides — and did worse. The climax is 16:51-52: 'Samaria did not commit half of your sins... you have made your sisters appear righteous by all your abominations which you have committed.' The city that received the most grace committed the most sin. Greater privilege means greater accountability (Amos 3:2; Luke 12:48)."
