          "body": "The chapter could have ended at 16:58 — 'You have borne the penalty of your lewdness and abominations.' Judgment complete. But it does not. The 'nevertheless' of 16:60 is the theological turning point of the entire chapter and one of the most important single words in the prophetic corpus. God will remember the covenant 'in the days of your youth' — returning to the founding moment of grace in the field, not to the Mosaic covenant which Jerusalem broke, but to the deeper layer of covenantal intention that precedes even Sinai. He will establish an 'everlasting covenant' (*berit olam*) — a phrase that elsewhere in the Old Testament signals the new covenant of Jeremiah 31:31-34 and Ezekiel 36:26-27. The restoration will not be restoration to Mosaic-era conditions; it will be something categorically new. Significantly, the restoration includes Sodom and Samaria alongside Jerusalem (16:53, 55) — the sisters Jerusalem had despised will share in her redemption, and the scope of the covenant widens beyond ethnic Israel to include those she regarded as categorically inferior. The restored Jerusalem will receive her sisters 'as daughters, but not because of your covenant' (16:61) — grace is not conditioned on Jerusalem's past or future performance. The purpose of the everlasting covenant is stated twice: 'you shall know that I am the LORD' (16:62), and the final verse names the posture of the forgiven: 'so that you may remember and be ashamed and never open your mouth anymore because of your humiliation, when I have forgiven you for all that you have done' (16:63). True restoration silences boasting. The forgiven do not celebrate their vindication; they are rendered speechless by a mercy that outstripped their worst sin."
